{"questionId":"25867","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the equation&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence or otherwise, determine the values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math> such that the equation has one positive&nbsp;and one negative real root.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>recognition that the product of the roots will be negative&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow><mi>k</mi></mfrac><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>\n<p>critical values&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;seen&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"25867","referenceCode":"22M.2.AHL.TZ1.8b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence or otherwise, determine the values of k such that the equation has one positive and one negative real root.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","